Intelligent Enterprise Operations Platform (IEOP)Solo-Developer Technical Blueprint & Execution Plan1. The "Zero-Burn" Architecture StackThis architecture replaces the costly, fragmented systems from the original blueprint with a cohesive, full-stack JavaScript/TypeScript environment.Frontend: React (Next.js) with TypeScript. Replaces the split web/mobile approach. Next.js handles the user interface, routing, and server-side rendering for the conversational dashboard.Backend: Node.js with Express or Fastify (TypeScript). Replaces the five distinct Python microservices. This single monolithic API handles authentication, document processing, and AI routing.Database & Vector Store: PostgreSQL with the pgvector extension. Replaces the split GCP Cloud SQL and Qdrant setup. This allows you to store relational user data and high-dimensional AI embeddings in the exact same database, drastically simplifying DPDP data erasure.AI Infrastructure: Google Gemini API. Gemini 3 Flash serves as the primary multimodal workhorse, while Gemini 2.5 Flash-Lite handles ultra-low latency routing tasks.2. Consolidated Database Schema (PostgreSQL)To maintain DPDP compliance while moving fast, the original five-table schema  is condensed into three highly functional tables.Users Table:id (UUID, Primary Key)email (Text, Unique)role (Enum: admin, user)deleted_at (Timestamp, Nullable) - Critical for DPDP "Right to Erasure" compliance; triggers soft deletes.Documents Table:id (UUID, Primary Key)user_id (UUID, Foreign Key)title (Text)ingestion_status (Enum: pending, processed, failed) Document_Chunks Table (The Vector Store):id (UUID, Primary Key)document_id (UUID, Foreign Key)content (Text) - The actual text chunk (e.g., 512 tokens).embedding (vector(1536)) - The generated mathematical embedding.3. The Node.js RAG Pipeline (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)Instead of relying on heavy Python libraries like LangChain, you will build a streamlined, native Node.js ingestion and retrieval flow.Phase A: Ingestion (Document Upload)Parse: The Node backend receives a PDF/text file via the Next.js frontend.Chunk: A simple JavaScript utility splits the text into chunks of ~512 tokens with a 128-token overlap.Embed: Node calls the embedding API (e.g., text-embedding-3-large) to convert each chunk into a vector.Store: Insert the chunks and their corresponding vectors directly into the Postgres Document_Chunks table using standard SQL INSERT statements.Phase B: Retrieval & Generation (User Query)Embed Query: The user submits a question in the chat interface. Node embeds this query text into a vector.Vector Search: Node executes a cosine similarity query in Postgres (SELECT content FROM Document_Chunks ORDER BY embedding <=> query_vector LIMIT 5). This retrieves the most semantically relevant information.Generate: Node injects these text chunks into a prompt and sends it to the Gemini 3 Flash API.Stream: The Gemini response is streamed back to the Next.js frontend via server-sent events (SSE).4. Step-by-Step Implementation PlanThis sequence is designed so you can build, test, and stabilize one layer before moving to the next, adhering to a rapid Test-Driven Development (TDD) cycle.Week 1: Infrastructure & Database FoundationStep 1: Initialize a Next.js (TypeScript) repository.Step 2: Set up a hosted PostgreSQL database (like Supabase or Neon) that natively supports the pgvector extension.Step 3: Write and execute the SQL migrations for the Users, Documents, and Document_Chunks tables.Step 4: Implement basic JWT authentication in your Node/Next.js backend to secure API routes.Week 2: The Ingestion APIStep 1: Build the Next.js frontend upload component.Step 2: Write the Node.js API route to accept file uploads.Step 3: Implement the text chunking logic in plain TypeScript.Step 4: Integrate the embedding API and write the Postgres INSERT queries to save vectors.Week 3: The Retrieval Pipeline & AI IntegrationStep 1: Write the Postgres SQL query to perform cosine similarity searches using pgvector.Step 2: Integrate the Google Gemini SDK into your Node backend.Step 3: Construct the RAG prompt template: "Context: [Injected DB Chunks] — Question: [User Query] — Answer based strictly on context.".Step 4: Implement response streaming from the backend to the frontend to ensure a snappy user experience.Week 4: Interface Polish & DPDP ComplianceStep 1: Finalize the Next.js chat interface, ensuring it handles markdown and loading states gracefully.Step 2: Implement the DPDP Right to Erasure. Write a single API endpoint that cascades a DELETE command from the Users table down to the Documents and Document_Chunks tables. Because everything is in Postgres, this is a simple SQL transaction, completely avoiding the complex synchronization issues of a split database architecture.


